# Workflow Rules

## Worktree Discipline
- At startup, discover and remember the branch or worktree assigned to your role.
- If your assigned worktree is `master`, work in the main project checkout on its current branch; do not expect or create a `.worktrees/<role>` directory for that role.
- Work only in your assigned branch or worktree.
- Do not inspect, diff, merge, or base work on another branch unless that branch is specifically named in a handoff or explicit user instruction.
- Do not run `./swarm` from an agent worktree to repair helper scripts. If `notify-agent.sh` is missing from PATH, stop and report the startup failure.

## Temporary Files
- Use `./tmp/` in your assigned worktree for temporary files; do not use `/tmp`.

## Logbook
- The harness owns all writes to `logbook.json`. Agents never write to it directly and must never commit it.
- `logbook.json` is gitignored and local per worktree. Do not hand-edit logbook entries.
- Use `notify-agent.sh send` and `notify-agent.sh receive` to trigger harness-managed logbook updates for sent, received, and queued entries.
- If a merge conflict occurs in `logbook.json`, keep all complete JSON entries from both sides and resolve chronologically when obvious.

## Handoff Format
- For every outgoing handoff, write only the role-specific handoff body to `./tmp/<target-role>-handoff.txt`, then send it with `notify-agent.sh send <target-role> --file ./tmp/<target-role>-handoff.txt`.
- `notify-agent.sh send` wraps the body with `message type`, `message id`, `sender role`, `target role`, and `message sequence` fields, archives the sent message, appends the sent logbook entry, and sends the message.
- `message id` values have this form: `handoff-YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS-sender-target-NNNNNN-XXXXXX` for handoffs and `resend-request-YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS-sender-target-NNNNNN-XXXXXX` for resend requests. `NNNNNN` is the per sender-target sequence number, and `XXXXXX` is a six-character random lowercase hexadecimal suffix.
- Start every handoff body with: `Re-read your role and constitution.`
- The specifier invents a short, stable handoff name for each accepted specification handoff.
- Every later handoff for that work must include the specifier handoff name.
- Handoff bodies must report only essential state, not prescribe process. After the opening line, include exactly these fields and no other prose: specifier handoff name, branch name, and 10-character commit hash.
- Do not tell the receiving role how to do its job, repeat your process, or ask it to continue sender-owned responsibilities. The normal request is: `Apply your own role rules to this state.`

## Receiving Handoffs
- When receiving any handoff or resend request, save the complete incoming message to `./tmp/incoming-handoff.txt` or another local file, then run `notify-agent.sh receive --file <saved-message-file>`.
- Process the handoff only if `notify-agent.sh receive` reports `OK to process` and exits successfully.
- If `notify-agent.sh receive` reports `DO NOT PROCESS`, do not merge, apply, or otherwise act on that handoff; the helper has detected an out-of-order, duplicate, or stale message and has requested any required resend.
- If a handoff sequence is greater than one more than the last processed sequence for that sender-target stream, `notify-agent.sh receive` sends a `resend-request` for the missing sequence range including the out-of-order handoff itself.
- If a `resend-request` is received, `notify-agent.sh receive` resends the archived requested messages and exits without role-specific work.
- After receiving a handoff, merge the sender branch state identified by the handoff branch name and 10-character commit hash into your assigned branch before applying your own role rules.
- When receiving a handoff, ignore sender process narrative and decide next actions only from your own role prompt, the constitution, and the current project state.

## Queued Messages
- If one or more messages arrive while you are busy:
  - Save each complete message as its own file in a local untracked `pending-messages/` directory in your assigned worktree.
  - Name queued message files with this format: `PP-YYYYMMDD-HHMMSS-source.txt`, where `PP` is the two-digit priority.
  - Use priority `00` for QA handoffs to specifier, coder, cleaner, architect, or hardender.
  - Use priority `50` for normal messages unless a role prompt or explicit user instruction sets a different priority.
  - Finish the current job before acting on queued messages.
  - After the current job is complete and any required handoff has been sent, process queued message files in sorted filename order.
  - Before removing any queued handoff file, run `notify-agent.sh receive --file <queued-message-file>` so the helper records the logbook entry and validates message sequence.
  - Process the queued handoff only if `notify-agent.sh receive` reports `OK to process`.
  - Delete each queued message file only after processing it. Do not use `rm -f`; use a non-forced deletion command so queue cleanup does not trigger escalation.

## Failure Conditions
- When you discover a defect you do not own, route it to the coder. Include: the failing step, the raw error output, your diagnosis, and a repro recipe. Autofixable issues (formatting, linting) are excepted — fix those in place.
- When a spec requirement conflicts with what the platform can actually deliver, stop and report to the user before proceeding. Do not work around the conflict silently. A workaround comment in code is the signal that this rule fired and was suppressed.
- If the expected git layout or assigned worktree is missing, stop and report instead of silently working in the wrong place.
